a female question whats the best way to handle your period and how to get rid of the pain and how to spend less money on your pads just try to take good care of yourself during your period eat healthy drink more water don't drink things with caffeine exercise get enough sleep etc that stuff will help a lot the things i mentioned can help with pain as well but if you're still hurting try taking something like midol or pamprin those help a lot if those don't help the pain talk to your doctor about getting some prescription strength pain reliever i had to do that because the meds i just mentioned didn't help me also tried tylenol and aleve tylenol didn't help at all and aleve helped but only when the pain wasn't severe and it helped me a lot as for spending less money on pads unless you buy an off brand like a store brand or buy them in bulk from someplace that sells items in bulk i'm not really sure how to save money on pads that's just one of those things you have to spend money on hope this helps Fecal incontinence Urinary incontinence Tylenol Migraine Anderson Cooper First aid Carpal tunnel syndrome Paracetamol Episodes of Lost (Season 1) Rich Mullins Non-Hodgkin's lymphoma The Catcher in the Rye Pitaten Chronic fatigue syndrome Similarities between the Bible and the Qur'an Breastfeeding RuneScape economy Mattress Medical prescription Stomach cancer Naproxen Characters in the Smurfs Castle of the Winds Osteoarthritis Wal-Mart Health insurance Piccolo Junior Saga Sears Holdings Corporation Charles Ponzi Insomnia Humphrey Bogart Knots Landing Ethical consumerism Leeds United F.C. Publicly funded medicine Addiction Eternal Sunshine of the Spotless Mind Hormone replacement therapy (trans) Hamster Mad Money Red Bull Crohn's disease Antidepressant Paget's disease of bone Canadian and American health care systems compared Coffee The Apprentice 2 Milton H. Erickson Psoriasis Grandview, U.S.A. Teen Girl Squad Ramen Social rule Illegal drug trade Papa's Got a Brand New Badge